    <div class="comment">
	    <a name="cid-1399025"></a>
	    <p class="text">My Mom taught me to make fudge, years ago. We used one of her old cookbooks - the recipe did not use corn syrup, marshmallows, etc. It did use lots of butter, sugar, milk, cocoa. It required cream of tartar, a thermometer or the ability to distinguish the various stages (soft ball stage for fudge), patience stirring and waiting for it to cool, as it cooled, a strong arm for beating it, and the talent for discerning the exact moment it was ready to go into the buttered square pan before it seized in the pot. I don't like any other fudge besides that homemade chocolate with walnuts. It was creamy with a very fine crystalline grain, and an ever so thin crystalline crust.  It was not even slightly taffy like -- as are the "fudges" sold commercially.  Ah, might have to make some this year.</p>
